ting model</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. For example, Perry Beeches, an ‘outstanding’ secondary school in Bi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rmingham has been able to open two</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">new</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> schools in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">deprived parts of the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> city</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> where parents have </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">not </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">previously </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">had access to the same standard of education</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. In others, successful schools have been able to complement their existing provision by opening different phases or types of school. For example, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in London,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> St Marylebone School has recently opene</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">d a Special school for pupils with speech, language and communication difficulties and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Burlington Danes Academy will </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">soon </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">open a primary school to feed into</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> its existing secondary school. And this growth hasn’t been limited just to Acad</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">emies.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Maintained </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size: