ont-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">during the pre</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">opening stage.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">For Special (and in some cases </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Alternative </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">P</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rovision</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">) Free Schools</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ir</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> support is essential since </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">L</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> must provide evidence of demand for their proposals.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Oversight and accountability </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">3.8</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Free schools are subject to greater examination than almost any other type of state</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">-funded</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> school. Not only are they subject to the same accountability framework</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">as </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">any Academy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> but they face additional levels of scrutiny. The political controversy which has surround</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the policy means that Free Schools are the subject of intense analysis from local and national media as well as other interest groups. Even </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">more important</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, because</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> parents have actively chosen a Free School, often before it even physically exists, they have high expectations of what the school will deliver and are more engaged in holding it to account.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">3.9</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Once open, Free Schools have the same legal status as Academies</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> which is formally set out in a Funding Agreement</span><a name="_ednref12"></a><a href="#_edn12">[12]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, signed by the Secretary of State and the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Company Limited by Guarantee that operates the new academy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. Free Schools are expected to adopt a model funding agreement which, amongst other </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">things, states that t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">hey must follow the School Admissions Code, be inspected by Ofsted, publish their results and provide a broad and balanced curriculum, which cannot teach anything counter to fundamental British values, or creationism.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">3.10</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There is a seven year notice period i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n standard Free School funding agreements</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">I</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">f a Free School is found to be in breach of it any time before then, the Secretary of State </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">has the power to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">terminate </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the agreement. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This power has proved reasonably</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> effective – it was the threat of terminating </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the funding agreement that allowed the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">DfE </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">take action </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in terms of the governance of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Al-Madinah</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in Derby</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">– requiring them </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">accept new </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">management</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> or face termination</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> It is worth noting however that there is no defined point at which an agreement is re</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">viewed and, apart from this power to terminate, there is no power to intervene or pass management of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a Free School or an </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">academy to someone else. The need for these wider powers and the standard period of funding agreements should be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">reviewed to ensure </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">that they allow swift and decisive action can be taken in cases where there are serious concerns about the school</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">3.11</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The EFA oversees the financial management and governance of Free Schools through a named contact for each school</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">who visits the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">m in thei</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> first term</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. DfE Education Advisers </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">also visit new schools </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in the autumn term of each of the first two years of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">operation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Finally, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Ofsted inspects the school within two years of opening </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">assessing against the same standards </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">required of all state schools. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> These assessments are used to identify potential risks to schools and risk rate each school, with particular concerns being escalated through further monitoring. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It was through this route that the issues at Discovery New School</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in Crawley</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> were identified </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">subsequently </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">addressed.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">3.12</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Secretary of State can take a number of actions in relation to failing Free Schools:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.7pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">—</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Allow Ofsted to follow its standard processes for all state schools through subsequent inspection and monitoring; </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.7pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">—</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">D</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">emand a compreh</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ensive </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">plan to address failure; </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.7pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">—</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Intervene to appoint and rem</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ove governors; </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.7pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">—</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Transfer the running of the school to a different Academy sponsor; or</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.7pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">—</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Terminate the school’s funding agreement and close the school</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">3.13</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Attention has been drawn to the weaknesses of a small number of the first Free Schools, which have been exposed either by inspection from Ofsted, investigation by the EFA or by individuals bringing matters to the attention of the DfE. In all cases the resp</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">onse has been both swift and practical. There is little evidence to suggest that intervention would have been any swifter if these schools had been s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ubject to LA oversight – for instance </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">there are currently more than 350 maintained schools in special measu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">res, nearly a third of which have had that status for more than a year.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 16.68pt; padding-left:1.32pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Approval and oversight: the future</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">4.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">If Free Schools are to reach their full potential in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">improving</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> standards</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">using their academy freedoms</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">introducing innovation into</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the system</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">allowing outstanding providers to open new schools, encouraging competition</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and increasing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the number of good school places in the system</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, it is important</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">that both the approval and oversight systems to which Free Schools are subject are designed to protec</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">t and encourage their distinctive features and the unique addition they make to the schools system</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">4.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Underlying these distinctive features is the fact that new </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">providers and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">innovations have </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the potential to raise educational standards </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">bring</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> challenge</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and competition to existing systems, even if this means creating a surplus of places. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Any </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">revisions to the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">approval </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">oversight systems</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, especially if they are designed </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to accommodate all a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">cademies or schools more widely, will </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">therefore </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">need to be caref</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ully assessed to ensure they do </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">not create unforeseen </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">barriers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> or stifle the development and potential of the Free School programme in particular</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">4.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This need is particularly a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">cute when it comes to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">approvals</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">process where it is important to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> ensure that good schools continue to be approved to open where they are needed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and wanted by local parents</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> – including</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> when they will be competing with existing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">underperforming </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">provision</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">4.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Local authorities and local schools, as providers with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">responsibil</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ity for managing and overseeing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">existing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">schools</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in a given region</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">may be inclined to resist </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">when it</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> comes to considering the introduction of alternative school</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> that might challenge the status quo. In light of this, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">NSN believes </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he approval process for Free Schools should remain independent of Local Authorities and other local existing providers. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">While it is undeniable the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Free School programme has a strong momentum behind it</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, the scale of growth</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, even in the medium term,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> is likel</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">y to be small enough that it should be possible to manage centrally.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">4.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Similarly, there are unique challenges in setting up an entirely new school and the right support and challenge is needed to ensure schools are set up to succeed not fail. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Strong accou</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ntability and performance </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">criteria</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> are vital to the success of the Free School programme. In NSN’s view, the current framework is robust and, alongside the Ofsted systems that apply to all schools, has allowed the DfE/EFA</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">/Ofsted</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to take swift and decisive </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">action where necessary.  However, given the rate of growth in the number of Free Schools and academies more widely, the DfE’s capacity to monitor risks centrally and interv</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ene where appropriate is becoming</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">stretched so it is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a sensible next step to fully </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">review</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> whether </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the current framework will remain fit for purpose</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">APPENDIX</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">current approval process</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As it stands, the approval process falls broadly into two phases:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">The application phase </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Groups wanting to set up a Free School rightly have to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">complete a demanding application process. Aside from the first year of the programme – when </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">groups completed a much briefer initial application and then received paid for support to turn this into a detailed </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">business </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">plan</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> – all Free School applicants have </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">had to undertake significant work </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">without any financial support (except those receiv</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ing small grants from NSN). Currently, this includes:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Developing detailed education</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> finance and governance plans</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> – which run to around 100 pages. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">By contrast, an Academy </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">sponsor can complete an application to take over a failing school in a largely pro-forma docum</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ent that runs to about 20 pages; </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Proving capacity and capability to run a successful school</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> – which must include access to expertise in education, finance, gove</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rnance and other relevant areas, such as marketing. All individuals involved in the application are also vetted by the DfE’s due diligence team for their suitability to be involved in a school; and  </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Proving evidence of need for the school</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">–</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">which must sh</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ow that there is a case for the school in terms of demand from those who could attend the school and that locally there are insufficient school places and/or high numbers of children being educated in underperforming schools. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">To gather evidence of demand</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, M</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ainstream Free School</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> applicant</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">must</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> show </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">local parents</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">with</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> children of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">relevant</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> age</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to attend the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">chool when it opens</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, would choose it as a first choice, were it to open</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Special and AP Free School applicants must show that they have both the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> support of relevant parents/young people and in principle financial commitments from relevant commissioners to purchase places at the school</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, over and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> above the central funding (£10,000 and £8</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">000</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> respectively) available to them</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">I</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">deally</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, applicants have to show that the school would be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">several times oversubscribed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in its first two years of operation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Once submitt</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ed, these applications are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">assessed by dedicated teams at the DfE/EFA and, where they have been submitted by an existing Acade</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">my sponsor, discussed with the Academies division to analyse the sponsor’s capacity to expand further.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Following this, a number of applicants are invited for interview by a panel which includes representatives from the DfE, EFA, external educational advis</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ers and independent experts. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The rigour of the application phase can be seen in’ the relatively low success rate of applicants, with only 26% of the 1103 applications received by the DfE being progressed to the pre-opening phase</span><a name="_ednref13"></a><a href="#_edn13">[13]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">The pre-opening phas</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">e</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">If successful </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">at interview</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, groups are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> then</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">provisionally </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">‘approved’ to open a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Free S</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">chool</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. Groups receive funding from the DfE</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (currently £220,000 for primary schools and £300,000 for secondary/all-through schools) in order to ensure the school ready to open – including recruiting staff, developing education plans and policies, building financial systems and recruiting pupils. Th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ey must also conduct a statutory consultation with the local community to ask whether stakeholders believe the school should open, and respond to any concerns.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Groups also receive substantial support at this stage with finding, securing and developing a s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ite with the EFA taking all key decisions. Aside from this, the role of the DfE is largely to provide oversight and challenge to the project – through a dedicated project lead, education and finance advisers, who hold regular checkpoint meetings to review </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">its progress. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">If </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">this is found to be unsatisfactory at any stage then the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">project may be cancelled, or the opening </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of the school delayed. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Before being allowed to open, the school must also </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">pass</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> two further requirements. First, it is inspected by</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Ofsted t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">o ensure </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">that it meets </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">necessary standards</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> around the quality of its premises and the provision of policies relating to issues such as the welfare, health and safety of pupils</span><a name="_ednref14"></a><a href="#_edn14">[14]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. Secondly, DfE officials must </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">conduct an</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> assessment of the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Free School</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">’s impact</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> on other schools in the area. Only at this stage, if all other requirements have been fulfilled, will the Secretary of State sign a funding agreement with the school which allows it to formally open. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_edn1"></a><a href="#_ednref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt"> Of the 24 Free Schools which opened in 2011: four were rated outstanding; 14 were rated good; five required improvement and one was inadequate. Comparative data here: </span><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/256056/131107_Letter_to_Baroness_Jones_of_Whitchurch.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; text-decoration:underline">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/256056/131107_Letter_to_Baroness_Jones</span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; text-decoration:underline">_of_Whitchurch.pdf</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_edn2"></a><a href="#_ednref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt"> NAO </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">Establishing Free Schools Report (December 2013) </span><a href="http://www.nao.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/10314-001-Free-Schools-Book.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.nao.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/10314-001-Free-Schools-Book.pdf</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_edn3"></a><a href="#_ednref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt"> Based on analysis of data from Ofsted </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">dataview</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt"> (</span><a href="http://dataview.ofsted.gov.uk/"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; text-decoration:underline">http://dataview.ofsted.gov.uk/</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">) as at October 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_edn4"></a><a href="#_ednref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">Broadly, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">Forest schools use outdoor education in which pupils learn personal, social and technical skills such as team building and risk management in a forest or woodland area. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">Some elements of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">curriculum </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">can </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">be delivered outside and forest schools follow a mo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">del </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">of child initiated learning with a focus on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">building a relationship between the pupil and the natural world.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_edn5"></a><a href="#_ednref5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt"> Reform report – </span><a href="http://reform.co.uk/resources/0000/0385/Plan_A__FINAL.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">Plan A+: Unleashing the potential of academies</span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; text-decoration:underline"> (March </span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; text-decoration:underline">2012)</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt"> by Dale Bassett et al.  Comparisons are with number of Academies that have used or plan to use these freedoms</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_edn6"></a><a href="#_ednref6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt"> Full information on this survey can be found in the NSN data release </span><a href="http://www.newschoolsnetwork.org/sites/default/files/Free%20School%20data%20release%20-%20FINAL_0.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.newschoolsnetwork.org/sites/default/files/Free%20School%20data%20release%20-%20FINAL_0.pdf</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_edn7"></a><a href="#_ednref7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt"> This is based on</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt"> NSN’s internal data-gathering. Schools self-identify their nature.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_edn8"></a><a href="#_ednref8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt"> Data downloaded from </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">Edubase</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt"> November 2013: </span><a href="http://www.education.gov.uk/edubase/home.xhtml"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.education.gov.uk/edubase/home.xhtml</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_edn9"></a><a href="#_ednref9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt"> KIPP Schools (Knowledge is Power Partnership) base their model on the belief that every student can</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt"> learn and achieve regardless of background. Teachers and leaders are focussed on the over-riding goal of preparing KIPP students to “succeed in college and live choice filled lives.”</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_edn10"></a><a href="#_ednref10">[10]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt"> Uncommon run high performing Charter Schools in New York, New Jersey a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">nd Massachusetts and focus on giving every student the opportunity of a college education, naming their classrooms after top colleges such as Harvard and Yale. They focus on developing outstanding teaching and teachers as the most important driver of stude</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">nt attainment.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_edn11"></a><a href="#_ednref11">[11]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt"> </span><a href="http://www.nao.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/10314-001-Free-Schools-Book.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.nao.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/10314-001-Free-Schools-Book.pdf</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_edn12"></a><a href="#_ednref12">[12]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt"> The model funding agreement for Free Schools can be accesse</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt"> here:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt"> </span><a href="http://www.education.gov.uk/schools/leadership/typesofschools/freeschools/b00222077/pre-opening/funding-agreement"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.education.gov.uk/schools/leadership/typesofschools/freeschools/b00222077/pre-opening/funding-agreement</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_edn13"></a><a href="#_ednref13">[13]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt"> NAO Report, p 14. </span><a href="http://www.nao.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/10314-001-Free-Schools-Book.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.nao.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/10314-001-Free-Schools-Book.pdf</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_edn14"></a><a href="#_ednref14">[14]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt"> </span><a href="http://www.ofsted.gov.uk/sites/default/files/documents/registration-forms-and-guides/p/Pre-registration%20regulatory%20check%20sheet%20for%20an%20academy%2C%20free%20school%2C%20studio%20school%20or%20university%20technical%20college%20%28UTC%29.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.ofsted.gov.uk/sites/default/files/docum</span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; text-decoration:underline">ents/registration-forms-and-guides/p/Pre-registration%20regulatory%20check%20sheet%20for%20an%20academy%2C%20free%20school%2C%20studio%20school%20or%20university%20technical%</span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; text-decoration:underline">20college%20%28UTC%29.pdf</span></a><a name="_GoBack"></a></p></body></html>